  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">5.III. Accelerating the implementation of the chemicals and waste Multilateral Environmental Agreements and achieving the targets of related Sustainable Development Goals for improved human health and a clean environment</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project objective is to enhance capacities of Parties to the Chemicals and Waste multilateral environmental agreements (MEAs), in particular the Basel, Rotterdam, Stockholm and Minamata Conventions, and of stakeholders of the Strategic Approach to International Chemicals Management (SAICM), to implement the MEAs and SAICM and foster a holistic and cooperative approach to addressing chemicals and waste among countries and sectors.

Chemicals are essential for modern societies. They provide many desired functions, not only in meeting our immediate needs, but also to a certain extent contributing to a low carbon future of our society. However, it is now well recognized that chemical pollution due to unsound management of chemicals and waste may cause a wide range of adverse impacts. To achieve sound management of chemicals and waste worldwide, MEAs including the Basel, Rotterdam, Stockholm and Minamata Conventions, and SAICM have been established to address specific chemicals and waste through international cooperative actions. However, the latest Global Chemicals Outlook II concludes, &amp;ldquo;the sound management of chemicals and waste, and minimizing adverse impacts, will not be achieved by 2020&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;business as usual is therefore not an option&amp;rdquo;. Key barriers to countries and stakeholders&amp;rsquo; taking action include (1) inadequate and/or non-sustainable financial means, (2) inadequate awareness on chemicals and waste, (3) inadequate technical capacity to implement sound management of chemicals and waste, and (4) a lack of holistic cooperative approaches to addressing chemicals and waste.</narrative>
  </description>
